  "text": "p53 drives p21 heterogeneity in unperturbed conditions. We sought to determine factor(s) driving heterogeneity in p21 levels. Multiple transcription factors have been linked to p21 regulation [CITATION_1] ; the best characterized being p53. Depletion of p53 by siRNA resulted in a large reduction in basal p21-GFP levels, compared to control siRNA ( Fig. 2a ; Supplementary  Fig. 3a-c) . Furthermore, G1 length became more homogeneous (Fig. 2a) and no cells analysed entered G1pm arrest (Fig. 2b) . Thus, both G1pm arrest and G1 delay are p53-dependent, and p53 signalling is necessary for p21 accumulation in hTert-RPE1 cells. . (e) Correlation in G1 p21-GFP levels between sister cells-G1 Daughter1 (G1 D1 ) and G1 Daughter2 (G1 D2 ; n ¼ 62, Pearson's Correlation R ¼ 0.81** (Po0.01)). Data points are coloured to represent correlation between G1 length in each daughter cell, calculated as the difference between the maximum and minimum G1 length divided by the sum of the sister G1 lengths, n ¼ 62.",
